Date: 2/5/1974
Source: Otago Daily Times
Author:
Vol / Page: 10
Edition:
Quote: Pavlova cake has for so many years been a staple of any party ... [`Urumoa' writing from Oamaru searched old recipe books and found] 1. Meringue cake, copied from the Otago Daily Times of June 26, 1934. This is the same as the modern pavlova without the one teaspoon of cornflour. 2. `Cookery' by Miss I. Finlay [see preceding entry], published by the Dunedin City gas department, third edition, about 1933. ... recipe No. 452 for meringue sponge sandwich or pavlova cake, for which I was surprised to see she suggested sandwich tins or a special pavlova tin. When I bought one of the latter recently I thought they were something new! 3. Two privately-published but undated recipe books from Invercargill which must be pre-1933, as we left the city in that year. Both contain recipes for pavlova. [But do they specify the name `pavlova' ? HWO] It would be interesting ... to find out when the teaspoon of vinegar and teaspoon of cornflour were added to the recipe as they give pavlovas their marshmallow-type centre. The recipes I have mentioned list only egg whites, sugar, vanilla and a pinch of salt. [Pavlova visited New Zealand in 1926: Auckland May 1926, Wanganui, Hastings, Napier, Palmerston North, Wellington, Christchurch, Timaru, Dunedin: see Maurice Hurst <i>Music and the Stage in New Zealand.</i>Pavlova cake has for so many years been a staple of any party ...
